RFC 001: Declarative Postgres (DPG) v1.0Status: Proposed Technical SpecificationAuthor: GeminiVersion: 1.0.0Scope: Ergonomic, Declarative Superset for PostgreSQL 14+1. Executive SummaryDeclarative Postgres (DPG) is a structural superset of PostgreSQL SQL designed to shift database management from an imperative "action-based" workflow (CREATE, ALTER, DROP) to a "state-based" configuration workflow. By utilizing hierarchical scoping and removing imperative verbs, DPG provides a high-level source of truth for database architecture.The DPG compiler transforms these configurations into standard PostgreSQL DDL, which is subsequently processed by the Supabase Declarative Schema engine to generate safe, transactional migrations.2. Fundamental Philosophy2.1 The "No-Verb" MandateIn DPG, the existence of a definition block is the instruction for existence. There are no CREATE, ALTER, or DROP keywords. If a block is present in the source, the object must exist in the database. If it is removed from the source, the object is dropped.2.2 Native Logic ParityDPG is not a new database language; it is a wrapper. All internal parameters (types, constraint logic, search configurations) remain 100% native to PostgreSQL. DPG only modifies the "container" and "lifecycle" of the code.2.3 Scoped InheritanceObjects inherit their schema, ownership, and target relations (e.g., table targets for indices) based on their physical nesting in the code, eliminating the redundant ON table_name or IN schema_name syntax.3. Scoping and Organization3.1 The Global Node (Database)The top-level container is the database. This is declared once at the top of every file.Rule: All files sharing the same database name are merged into a single state specification.Syntax: database <name>3.2 The Physical Node (Schema)Defines a PostgreSQL namespace.Rule: A file-level schema (schema name) prevents any other schemas from being defined in that file.Syntax: schema <name> [from <old_name>] { ... }3.3 The Logical Node (Group)A non-database container used strictly for developer organization within the .dpg source files.Rule: Groups have no impact on the generated SQL; they are purely for code readability.Syntax: group <name> { ... }4. The TABLE EntityThe table is the primary unit of state. It is divided into logical sections to group sub-entities.4.1 Structural Sectionscolumns: Defining the data fields.indices: Defining performance structures.constraints: Defining data integrity (Check, Unique, Foreign Key).policies: Defining Row Level Security (RLS).4.2 Comprehensive Table Syntaxtable users from legacy_users {
    columns {
        id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid();
        email text unique not null;
        
        -- Block Mode Column
        bio text {
            comment "User biography in markdown";
        }
        
        -- Rename with type
        contact_email text from old_email;
    }

    indices {
        idx_users_email unique (email);
        idx_bio_search using gin (to_tsvector('english', bio));
    }

    constraints {
        min_email_length check (char_length(email) > 3);
        fk_org_id (org_id) references organizations(id);
    }

    policies {
        enable row level security;
        view_self for select using (id = auth.uid());
        update_self for update using (id = auth.uid()) with check (true);
    }

    comment "Primary identity table for the application";
    owner "admin_role";
}
5. Programmable Objects (Functions & Triggers)5.1 Functions and ProceduresDPG streamlines function definitions by removing the RETURNS keyword, the AS $$ delimiters, and the mandatory BEGIN/END blocks.Signature: function <name>(<params>) <return_type>Logic Extraction: The compiler treats the content of the block as the function body. Metadata keys (language, comment) are extracted first.function calculate_tax(price numeric, rate numeric) numeric {
    language plpgsql
    comment "Calculates VAT based on region"

    DECLARE
        total numeric;
    total := price * rate;
    RETURN total;
}
5.2 TriggersTriggers are defined at the top level or within a table. They bind an existing function to a lifecycle event.trigger on_user_created {
    after insert on users
    for each row
    execute function handle_new_user()
}
6. Global Objects6.1 Custom Types (Enums & Composites)Native PostgreSQL types are defined without the CREATE TYPE or AS keywords.enum order_status { 'pending', 'processing', 'shipped', 'delivered' }

type address {
    street text,
    city text,
    zip int
}
6.2 Extensions and Sequencesextension "pgcrypto"
extension "postgis" { comment "Required for spatial queries" }

sequence user_id_seq {
    start 100
    increment 10
}
7. The "Intent-Driven" Rename LogicThe from keyword is the primary mechanism for state reconciliation. It allows the DPG compiler to provide "hints" to the Supabase migration engine.7.1 Rename Mapping TableActionDPG SyntaxRename Column<new_name> <type> from <old_name>Rename Tabletable <new_name> from <old_name> { ... }Rename Schemaschema <new_name> from <old_name> { ... }Rename Typeenum <new_name> from <old_name> { ... }8. Dual Definition Modes (Metadata Handling)To maintain 100% parity with PG's COMMENT ON and ALTER OWNER features, DPG objects support two modes.8.1 Inline Mode (Fast)Standard SQL parameters on a single line.column email text unique8.2 Block Mode (Rich)A {} scope allowing for DPG-specific metadata keys.column email {
    text unique; -- Standard SQL followed by ;
    comment "Used for login";
    owner "security_admin";
}
9. Compilation & Reconciliation WorkflowGather: Scan project directory for .dpg files.Contextualize: Link files sharing a database header into a Dependency Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG).Compile: Output a single schema.sql (snapshot) consisting of standard, verbose PostgreSQL DDL (including rename comments).Diff (Supabase): The Supabase CLI compares this snapshot against the live database or a shadow database.Generate: Supabase outputs a standard .sql migration file in supabase/migrations/.Apply: Migrations are applied to the database, ensuring the live state matches the DPG source.10. ConclusionDPG v1.0 eliminates the friction of manual migration management by providing a clean, hierarchical, and verb-less syntax for PostgreSQL. It preserves the power of native SQL while adding the safety and ergonomics of a modern configuration language.
